7. **Exceptions requiring explicit acceptance:**
   - New color values or theme colors
   - New font configurations
   - New reusable components
   - New utility functions
   - New constants or types
   - New CSS classes or Tailwind extensions

### 4. Code Quality Standards

#### Components
- Use functional components with TypeScript
- Export components as named exports from their own files
- Components should be pure and reusable
- Use props interfaces defined in the same file or imported from types
- Keep components focused and single-purpose

#### Naming Conventions
- **Files**: PascalCase for components (e.g., `UserCard.tsx`), camelCase for utilities (e.g., `formatDate.ts`)
- **Components**: PascalCase (e.g., `UserProfile`)
- **Functions/Utilities**: camelCase (e.g., `formatCurrency`)
- **Constants**: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `MAX_FILE_SIZE`)
- **Types/Interfaces**: PascalCase (e.g., `UserProfileProps`)
- Keep names simple, clear, and descriptive
- Avoid abbreviations unless widely understood

#### TypeScript
- Use strict TypeScript
- Define proper types for all props, functions, and data structures
- Avoid `any` type - use proper typing or `unknown` if necessary
- Export types from dedicated type files when shared

#### Tailwind CSS
- **ALL Tailwind utility classes are PROHIBITED**
- This includes ALL categories: spacing (mb-*, mt-*, px-*, etc.), layout (max-w-*, min-h-*, etc.), positioning (left-*, top-*, transform, etc.), flex/display (flex, items-*, justify-*, etc.), typography (text-*, font-*, etc.), and ANY other utility classes
- Use inline styles with constants instead of Tailwind classes
- Avoid custom CSS unless absolutely necessary (then use CSS modules)
- Standardize color usage - reuse existing color values
- Create reusable component patterns, not duplicate classes

